<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="graphics/fastrec1.gif" ALT="Fast Recovery Diodes" WIDTH=225 HEIGHT=77>
<!--IMG SRC="graphics/fastrec2.gif" ALT="Fast Recovery Diodes" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=51>
<!--IMG SRC="graphics/fastrec3.gif" ALT="FReDs" WIDTH=113 HEIGHT=38></CENTER>
<p>
The six most important characteristics of an ultra-fast rectifier are (1)
softness of recovery, (2) storage charge, (3) avalanche energy handling, (4)
reverse blocking voltage, (5) reverse leakage current, and (6) maximum
operating temperature. IR offers two types of ultra-fast rectifiers. A
traditional line offers switching speeds of less than 200 nanoseconds, and our
advanced-technology line uses the HEXFRED<sup>&reg;</sup> process for recovery times as low
as 19 nanoseconds, and a "soft" recovery of the reverse current. The die size,
package style and reverse voltage determine the current rating of the part.
Package offerings range from surface mount and axial-leaded types with ratings
of a few amps, to large dual-diode modules with ratings in excess<i> </i>of 400
amperes. Continued increases in the switching frequency of motor control, UPS
and modular power supplies will demand new packages and device types.
Ultra-fast diodes represent the fastest growing segment of the rectifier
market.<p>
</TD>
